Look at subset of data

xts is optimised for financial datasets: If xts does not have data for given time periods, even whole days then it won’t plot that. This means that weekends are omitted from fx charts by design, just like you want.

chartSeries(mybars120, name="GBPJPY 2-minute bars", subset="2014-10-29::")

chartSeries(mybars120, name="GBPJPY 2-minute bars", subset="2014-10-29 10:00:00/2014-10-29 11:00:00")

Select charting colour themes

We can customise the colour and display themes of the charts.

whiteTheme <- chartTheme("white")
names(whiteTheme)
##  [1] "fg.col"       "bg.col"       "grid.col"     "border"

Example of white Background theme

Many traders prefer the black background, but that is not the only colour scheme available in quantmod. Below I illustrate the white background theme.

whiteTheme <- chartTheme("white")
whiteTheme$bg.col <- "white"
whiteTheme$dn.col <- "pink"
whiteTheme$up.col <- "lightgreen"
whiteTheme$border <- "lightgray"

chartSeries(mybars120, name="GBPJPY 2-minute bars", subset="2014-10-29 10:00:00/2014-10-29 11:00:00", theme=whiteTheme)

Chart with 1 minute data

whiteTheme$dn.col <- "red"
chartSeries(zwin1, name="GBPJPY 1-minute bars", 
            subset="2014-10-29 10:00:00/2014-10-29 10:20:00", theme=whiteTheme)

Technical Trading Rules

whiteTheme$dn.col <- "red"
chartSeries(zwin1, name="GBPJPY 1-minute bars", 
            subset="2014-10-29 10:00:00/2014-10-29 15:20:00", 
            theme=whiteTheme,
            TA="addBBands()")

MACD

whiteTheme$dn.col <- "red"
chartSeries(zwin1, name="GBPJPY 1-minute bars", 
            subset="2014-10-29 13:30:00/2014-10-29 15:20:00", 
            theme=whiteTheme,
            TA="addMACD()")

Relative Strength Index - RSI

whiteTheme$dn.col <- "red"
chartSeries(zwin1, name="GBPJPY 1-minute bars", 
            subset="2014-10-29 13:30:00/2014-10-29 15:20:00", 
            theme=whiteTheme,
            TA="addRSI()")
